# Spidey Crawler — Project Conventions

## Stack
- **Monorepo:** pnpm workspaces (`apps/api`, `apps/web`)
- **Backend:** Nest.js 11, TypeScript (strict), better-sqlite3, worker_threads
- **Frontend:** Next.js 15 (App Router), React 19, Tailwind CSS v4
- **Real-time:** Server-Sent Events (SSE) via RxJS Subject

## Key Constraints
- No external scraping/parsing libraries (no Cheerio, jsdom, Puppeteer, Scrapy)
- Native `fetch` + regex for HTML parsing
- SQLite only (WAL mode) — no external DB servers
- Single-machine concurrency via `worker_threads`

## Code Style
- TypeScript strict mode in both apps
- Nest.js conventions: modules, services, controllers, dependency injection
- Shared types in `apps/api/src/common/interfaces.ts` — frontend mirrors in `apps/web/src/lib/types.ts`
- No comments that just narrate what code does — only explain non-obvious intent or trade-offs
- Prefer `const` over `let`; avoid `any`

## Architecture Rules
- URLs are marked visited **on enqueue** (INSERT with UNIQUE constraint), not after fetch
- Back pressure: skip enqueuing new links when queue exceeds ceiling (never stop processing)
- Worker threads are ephemeral — one per URL, terminate after task
- SSE events flow: CrawlerService → SSEService (RxJS Subject) → CrawlerController (@Sse) → Frontend (EventSource)
- Database operations are synchronous (better-sqlite3) — no async/await needed for DB calls

## File Layout
- Backend source: `apps/api/src/`
- Frontend source: `apps/web/src/`
- SQL schema: `apps/api/src/database/schema.sql` (copied to dist via nest-cli assets)
- Worker thread: `apps/api/src/crawler/worker/crawler.worker.ts`

## Running
- `pnpm dev` — starts both API (:3001) and web (:3000)
- Next.js rewrites `/api/*` to `localhost:3001` — frontend never calls :3001 directly
